But Yadi S. the M.A that was seeing us was not doing everything correctly. I know because i'm in the medical field myself. She told my son that his blood pressure was perfect for a 21 year old. But it was 127/80. That is abnormal and I told her that it wasn't normal at all. But she kept saying it was. Giving any patient the wrong information can be life and death. Especially if its not handled right away.  So my son didn't know his height, Yadi the M.A told him that it didn't matter. Mind you within the weight loss program you get shots and pills so you have to make sure everything is correct.  I explained to Yadi that stadiometer is right there on the wall. Yadi then talked under her mouth and kept on with her attitude. So then she was then having an attitude and said we can walk over to measure his height. He is 6 ft 2 inches. She didn't wanna raise the bar to get his height. So my son was slumped over trying to lift it. So instead I then proceeded to do it myself. Of course i'm getting a little annoyed because if shes not doing this 100% correct then what else is she doing? We then finally get into the room. A couple  of minutes go by and Yadi walks in. She first tells my son the wrong amount of shots that he would be getting. Then once again I had to correct her and say the right amount. She proceeds to give my daughter and I the shots. When she was giving us the shots she kept mentioning to rub it in. Using a angry tone in her voice. So fast forwarding my son had to get an EKG, which scans your heart. She kept taking him to a different room away from me just because she  didn't want me to hear the information that she was giving my son. I finally asked her "Why are you taking my son to a separate room?" She then told me that she has to keep redoing the test because it keeps telling her that his heart isn't getting enough oxygen. Which I kept telling her earlier that his blood pressure was abnormal but she kept fighting me on it saying that it was totally normal.  I even googled a blood pressure chart for adults to show Yadi that the systolic mm (upper number) between the rang of 120-129 and the Diastolic mm (lower number) is consider to be in the elevated range. I explain to Yadi that diagnosing someone without the proper information , can affect someone's life. Yadi started to yell and explain that she was "right", causing a scene. So because of the bad information that she kept fighting me on earlier it turns out that I was 1 right and the doctor confirmed that his blood pressure was to high. 2 The test from the EKG showed that his heart was not getting enough oxygen and needed to be rushed to the hospital. The doctor told me that my son was on the verge of either having a heart attack. Which then I had to rush into mom mode and take care of my son which I did. <userid>103762204590095059509<//userid><Resp>{'time': 1579639671254, 'text': "Mrs Boykin we would first like to thank you for the review of your sons visit with our weight loss program. We would like to respond to some of the points you made in your review. First let me start by saying all our staff is trained and highly motivated to deliver the best care possible to every one of our patients. I know you mention you are in the Healthcare field which is great but you are not trained in our medical weight loss program. You mentioned your sons blood pressure was not normal specifically the systolic number, or bottom number.  Normal blood pressure is considered to be anything below 120/80. Hypertension is defined as blood pressure of 130/80 or higher.  Your son's blood pressure was in range. One of the things we do on your first visit is an Electrocardiogram or EKG which could indicate a problem or issue with your heart. We do this for several reasons but the biggest being the medication we dispense can elevate your heart rate and is not suitable for everyone. This should be done always before dispensing this medication for the first time. We would not be doing our job as Medical Professionals if we failed to do every step. If this is abnormal the provider may refer you back to your Primary for a cardiac consult to be cleared to take the medication or in some cases refer to the Emergency Room. This is not done unless the provider feels it is a necessary step. As for our staff everyone is required to wear a name badge when on the floor working so names are easily accessible to all. We are sorry you feel like your son had a bad experience but we feel he got the service he deserved and needed at the time he was seen. We hope to continue to see you and your family in our weight loss program and hope your son is feeling better. Have a wonderful day."}</Resp>< date>

< text>
My family moved here from Washington a year ago and we have been to several hospitals/doctors over the last several months for different reasons and have always left unsatisfied.  My boyfriend had a motorcycle crash and had severe road rash in which the hospital he went to didn't even treat him so after being let down so many times my hopes of being treated right were not very high.

We walked into West Point Medical Center 3 days after his crash to have them look at his wounds and re-wrap them since his own doctor's office wouldn't answer the phone.  We were very satisfied with West Point Medical to say the least.  Intake process with Rafael was painless and didn't take too long considering it was an urgent care clinic.

When we were finally seen, we weren't left in a room for hours.  Given that it was Raj's last shift before leaving town for a while, you'd think he'd be in a hurry, but he took the time to carefully look at the wounds and redress and offered for us to come back to redress the wounds if we needed.  Bridget and the ex-tern JB were also very helpful and we definitely didn't even feel like we were in a urgent care clinic.  All were very friendly and made this visit very painless and definitely will be back if we ever have to ,hopefully not though...no more accidents!

Thank you West Point Medical Center!!</text>

<userid>116647522693833960231<//userid><time>1620804230848</time><resp>None</resp>< review>
My child was here recently and I feel like this place can be very helpful if the child is wanting the help and especially if they have a strong support system. I liked that when I called I was treated with respect, my daughter was happy with the place. The only thing I didn't like was the "No Visits" rule due to Covid 19. I understand, but I feel like they could at least allow one parent/guardian a visit or something. The times they had to call parents or family was very limited and I missed my baby terribly. However I was extremely grateful that she would get help to be around for me to miss her when she's away, so for that I can't complain too much. My only issue with the entire place was when she was released, getting her prescriptions filled was extremely frustrating and hard to do. They were supposed to already be called in and ready to get picked up the same day. I went in the following morning, and still they didn't have my prescription, they said the hospital didn't fax the right info and it was signed by an RN, not my daughters actual Dr.
Overall I was happy with the place despite the reviews that are on the negative side.</review>

<Rating>1<//Rating>< Review>
IF YOU HAVE ANY CHOICE, DO NOT COME HERE. I admitted myself voluntarily to heritage oaks for a 72 hour hold. There are VERY few people at this hospital who actually showed genuine care for the patients. The rest of the staff are only there to do the bare minimum of their job, including the psychiatrists. I was ‚Äúevaluated‚Äù for hardly 5 minutes by Dr. Berci. This amount of time is not nearly sufficient to properly evaluate a patient that you have no prior knowledge of. Other than this, many nurses were rude, and acted as if even asking for water was burdening them. Heritage oaks is a place where they lock up people in mental health crises, experiment with drugs on them, and then keep the patients there much longer than necessary just to milk as much money as possible out of their insurances. <gmapID>0x809ad937edd33fff:0xa812a96c69e1cd01< /gmapID>< Text>
TL;DR  Are you looking for an extended stay at inpatient facility where rarely see the light of day, will be treated worse than most prisoners are, and want to kill yourself more than you ever have in your whole life? Then Heritage Oaks Hospital is right for you!

This place is hell on Earth. I implore anyone who may consider putting a family member here or anyone who may end up here involuntarily or voluntarily to seek out any other facility. You will see a psychiatrist for roughly 5-10 minutes every other day. All but a single nurse, treated every patient there like absolute garbage. They ignore you for as long as humanly possible. I even witnessed people having sever panic attacks be completely ignored, even though they are sitting a few feet away with a clear line of site. They have simple lost any compassion or empathy that I doubt they ever had to begin with. You are trapped inside what is basically a hallway. Even with engaging with other patients you will likely find yourself bored, anxious, and claustrophobic the majority of the time due to the lack of stimuli. They offer crayons (continuing the theme of treating patients like incompetent children) but no paper on which to draw or write. You will be blessed with fresh air for some 10 minutes a day in a small, depressing courtyard surrounded my tall, menacing looking fences (it's quite the pick me up). But they don't stop at treating you like the scum of the Earth, they want to keep treating you terribly for as long as possible. All they care about is the hundreds of dollars a day it apparently costs to house the patients. EVERY single patient I was in with on a 51-50, was kept for an additional 72 hours past the legal hold. Why would they stop there if they only cared about money? Because only after six days are patients allowed to receive a Patient's Rights Advocate and actually refute their internment. Need even more examples of their money-hungry ways? One patient I was in with voluntarily checked themselves in, after which they put on involuntary hold, so they could no longer leave. A person who realizes that they should be in a safe environment for a time, then puts themselves into a safe environment was deemed unfit to make decisions for themselves and not allowed to leave when they thought that they were better?! You get a paper stating why you are put on continued hold by the psychiatrist. Most of the time it says some vague, nonsense about being at risk for suicide. Even though most of us bullshitted about how good the facility was and how we were improving so much to get out faster. My favorite reason someone received for staying though was that they were apparently an alcoholic and would relapse.  The funny thing was that person had never drank or done drugs. Either that's malpractice or a complete lack of actually getting to know your patients. Even if this place wasn't after money, they would still be the least caring, understanding, and helpful on the planet. I could go on forever about how bad this place is but to put it simply: If you end up at Heritage Oaks Hospital, YOU WILL NOT GET BETTER. They do not and will not put forth more than the bare-minimum, legal effort to support their jobs. People in medicine should be do it because they love medicine and people, not because it's a stable job. There were one or two RNs or LVNs there that did actually treat us like human beings. It was just such a rare occurrence in that place though; I honestly would not expect it.</Text>

< username>
Robin Looper</username>
< date>
1526539320227</date>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
I am giving them 5 stars and I hate pasta!!!

We were greeted by two very friendly ladies and seated right away. I went to the restroom and it was dirty but as soon as I told the Hostess she went right to work on cleaning it up. This was the fault of a guest and the employee handled it immediately. So, I didn't minus a star.

Our Server Kelly was very personable and attentive and she always had a sense of urgency in taking care of our needs. The Manager was on the floor helping get tables served and bussed but he still found the time to come by and ask us how our dinner was. The menu choices were mostly pasta but there were a few items I could choose from that weren't. I would like to mention that they also had gluten free pasta choices. Kelly brought us salad and bread sticks quickly. I ordered the herb grilled salmon with broccoli and it was really delicious. I will have it again. Because I indulged in the bread sticks with the salad, I was able to take half of my dinner home and will have it for lunch tomorrow.

Some other things that factored into the five star rating were that every single employee that we came into contact with at the very least smiled at us. We were seated right in front of the kitchen door and the employees were going in and out of that door like crazy because the restaurant was busy. We didn't feel like we were at the kitchen door we felt like the employees were welcoming us and taking care of our needs as they were passing by our table. Kelly brought wine to the table and asked if we'd like a tasting. She also packaged our food at the table for us. The restaurant was decorated nicely and was well lit.

I work in guest service and this restaurant lacked nothing. I honestly didn't think I would give 5 stars to an Olive Garden but they deserve it. I will absolutly be a customer again!< /review>

<time>1533279379743< /time>< Rate>
1</Rate>
< review>
I have to think more than twice before posting this raiting. I like the place the ambience and all but, this is my second visit to this particular site.
In both ocations service was terrible. The worst was today.
We walked in around 8:50pm and the hostess told us that the waiting for a table was about 25 to 30 minutes. There was no one waiting and there were plenty of open tables. The hostess told us to go to the coffee area (bar) since they had couple of open tables there. Also, she stated that service would be the same as the restaurant area.
After we sat at a table, took about 15 minutos before someone come by to ask if we have been helped. The person said "I will be helping you, I will be right back'".
Then 10 more minutes later another guy showed up and asked us the same thing again. At that time a table was open but dishes were on it, so I asked to a guy wearing the radio and mic, if we could move from the high table into the regular one. He told us to move then he will have some one right over to clean the table.
The server brought us bread and drinks after 15 minutes and dropped them on the dirty table. Then he stated that he would come back to clean it.
After few workers went by our table they just saw but said-did nothing.
Then our server came back and told us that he was very busy so, he wouldn't be able to clean the table.
5 minutes later a lady came by and ask us if we have finished?
We explained the situation to her so she went to get a tray and helped us cleaning the table.
They told us that they had run out of cheese first, then they told us that they had run out of salad too.
There were about 3 parties on the lobby waiting for a table so I can't imagine how they would serve them. Anyway, both of my experiences were about the same so definitely I am not recommending this place at all. Their price is not cheap and they do not care about customers at all. I could of enjoyed a better meal along good service in another place.
I will not recommend this place for dinner at all. Rather pay to go across to Chevy's or Black Angus were customer service is exceptional!!!!
I should of given them zero (0) stars they really deserved it!
I hope management sees this post.</review>

< Text>
Still good place to go if one is hungry, as I was.  They still have all you can eat soup, salad and breadsticks for a reasonable price with unlimited soda's.

This O.G. is close to the freeway, other shopping (i.e. Home Depot, Best Buys, etc), plenty of parking, but the disabled parking is awkward and when we visited around 4:30 on a Saturday it was busy (45 minute wait), so to avoid waiting (because I was hungry) we went directly into what they call a "caf√©" (bar friendly for kids) which was small and the booth seating was horrible where we had to get up and sit at the tall tables with stools.

The reason I didn't give this O.G. a 1-star (because the food was a lower quality then other O.G.'s) is because our waiter (a black gentleman) was great at customer service, very prompt, communicative and got the job done.

Although despite the waiters phenomenal customer service, I wouldn't return to this Olive Garden, nor recommend.  It needs much improvement, and a Bar needs to be a Bar, so grown-ups can have a space to enjoy an alcohol beverage (watch the ball game) away from nonsense kids.<//Text>

I had a few questions for my order, and no I am totally not one of those complicated a-holes who write reviews cause of one bad experience. So I ask the waitress instead of ordering the baked ziti alforno I should just order the pasta bowl with the same sauce same cheese, would make sense to do it since its a little cheaper{and no I'm not a cheap-o either, pasta bowls are unlimited though and I was hungry!} so we agree on the pasta bowl. my friend orders his food. done deal. so like 45 min goes by, mind you the restaurant was empty, so for a 20 min waitlist to begin with was kinda dumb, and the bar had 2 other booths filled with customers,and our soup and salad finally come out. 45 min later...soup that is already cooked in the back probably made 4 hours prior, cause everything Is just scoop and go(I worked at Olive Garden tracy fyi) and it was cold. salad was soggy like she put the dressing on and left it sitting for 45 min.
